Caesar wrote his Commentaries in the midst of intense activity. They were jotted down as he journeyed and fought3 mere noteS‚ as it were, for future amplification. Hirtius says, “While others know how faultlessly they are written, 1 know with what ease and rapidity he dashed them off.''

For us the Gallie War has a peculiar interest because it treats of the peoples with whom we are most familiar and from whom most of us derive our ancestry. It marks, in a sense, the beginning ot modern history.
